##Li Tie: How to improve urban governance after an outbreak

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

As a result of a decision-making error in urban governance, resulting in a huge loss of the country as well as the whole society, what exactly is the problem? How to avoid similar mistakes in the future?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Li Tie

From January 23, Wuhan "closed city" began, the country's urban and rural response at the first level, the country mobilized comprehensive epidemic prevention. Although so far, the epidemic prevention situation in other cities and regions, except the key epidemic areas, has improved markedly, and the resumption of work and employment in some places and cities is also proceeding in a steady and orderly manner, however, some places and cities still have certain risks and fears, and still take high-level prevention and control measures.

This is arguably the first time since 1949 that an epidemic has triggered a national mobilization. As a result of an urban governance decision-making mistakes, resulting in the country and the whole society's huge losses, so far has not been released from the epidemic disaster.

We continue to carry out the general mobilization of Epidemic Prevention, whether to reflect on what we did wrong? Or what's the problem?

When many people reflect, they focus on accountability and the lack of a public epidemic prevention system. There are also many articles on urban governance and urban planning, urban Public Services and the right to speak and so on.

In fact, we have more reasons, through this epidemic on how to understand the problem of the city to sum up. Although we have been living in a period of rapid growth of urbanization, while learning from the experience of developed countries, but also out of their own unique path of urbanization. But even today, we don't seem to have studied China's urban problems.

Under-appreciated urban governance

By the end of 2019, China had a permanent urban population of 848 million, with a registered urban population of about 620 million. The urbanization rate of the permanent population has reached 60.6 percent, and the urbanization rate of the registered urban population is expected to reach 44.4 percent, a difference of 16.2 percentage points.

With such a large urban population and such rapid urbanization, it makes sense that we should make cities the top priority of governance. But so far, not only have we lagged far behind in our research, but we also lack systematic guidance on the operational level of our policies as compared with other areas, at least we rarely see a series of documents on urban governance in the policy documents issued. For example, the Central Committee's No. 1 Document is issued every year as an important policy guideline to guide rural development reform, but there is no corresponding document for urban development reform.

The current situation of China has already told people the following basic facts.

First, the proportion of the urban population in the total population has far exceeded the rural population, the total population has exceeded the combined population of the European Union, the United States and Japan, and the urban economy has accounted for more than 90% of the national economy.

Second, China's urban governance should be the focus of social governance, and rural governance can be driven by the city. Because China's urbanization process is still in progress, the future will not only improve the quality of urbanization, solve the problems of urbanization and settlement of the remaining agricultural transfer population, the new urban population will increase by at least 10 + percentage points, it is equivalent to hundreds of millions of rural and agricultural migrants who still need to settle in cities. To address the practical problems they face in urban life, the focus is on the city rather than on the countryside. In addition, the key to solving the problems of agriculture, rural areas and farmers lies in the cities. It lies in how the cities accept more rural people, how they promote the moderate scale operation of agriculture by reducing the number of farmers, and how they make effective use of rural resources through the development of non-agricultural industries, how to promote urban capital to bring rural development.

Third, the risk index of the society's future has shifted from the historical rural areas to the cities, that is to say, any crisis in the cities can affect the whole country. The Wuhan Epidemic has made us learn a bitter lesson. Future crises will not be limited to epidemics. Economic and social risks are everywhere. Even the smallest incident can cause a great disturbance.

Fourth, nearly 80 percent of Internet users are in cities. Modern Information Exchange and public opinion dissemination are carried by cities, and new technological innovations are also generated in cities. Of course, the most important technological changes are also translated into applications through changes in the needs of large urban populations.

Fifth, the future employment focus is also in the city. The development of industries and services of all sizes depends on cities, which also generate tax revenue for countries and cities. How to adapt to the development of industry, adapt to the employment needs of different population, how to play the role of cities of different sizes, has been placed in front of us to solve the problem.

Urban Governance is not the same as local governance

China's cities are different from those of the developed countries in Europe and the United States, as well as some East Asian countries influenced by their civilization systems. Urban Governance, which we have long valued, is biased towards being an important component of local governance in the national governance system, which, taken as a whole, is a top-down and bottom-up model, the main premise is to submit to the needs of national governance. In reality, the top down order was replaced by the market to a certain extent, but in many ways it was as if it was economic or social management, the traditional planned economy management still affects the national governance system in different forms, and then affects the implementation of urban policies. So city managers tend to place more emphasis on the requirements of higher-level governments, and seriously weaken their own economic and social development of the actual capacity to solve the problem.

Based on the above understanding, it is understandable why most city managers in the face of the problem, the first consideration is the requirements of the higher authorities. In the governance system of strengthening accountability, the so-called non-accountability mentality prefers to follow the advice of higher-level governments, or to learn from the experience and practice of higher-level governments, believing that at least there will be no major problems. If such a practice is followed in general daily work, there is no problem in maintaining the normal operation of the city's economy and society, but in the event of an emergency, the best time to solve the problem may be greatly delayed.

China is now the second largest economy in the world. The country's governance system should not only adapt to the changes in economic growth, but also pay more attention to the changes in urbanization, urban economic and social governance. The study of urban problems should not be confined to the idea of local governance, but should consider the particularity of urban governance as an economic and social unit with high concentration of population and factors.

Urban Governance is not just about urban construction

Looking back on the history since 1949, there have been many changes in the starting point of our study of urban problems, from the important carrier of industrialization to whether the supply of agricultural products can guarantee urban demand. After the 1980s, the focus of urban reform was the reform of state-owned enterprises, after which the local areas entered the era of vigorous urban construction. I remember in the 1990s when we went to the local cities, almost all the local government officials, and their understanding of urbanization was to build, to attract investment. In their work arrangements, urbanization related to the public services of the population, the government's agenda is often less important than construction and investment.

In the 21st century, the focus of urban development in China has shifted to real estate, because the income from real estate can meet the spending needs of local governments. Around the real estate development, the city has carried out a new round of development and construction, the city image has undergone earth-shaking changes. But when it comes to people, when it comes to public services, when it comes to the needs of urban residents, when it comes to the problems of the urban migrant population, although various requirements are often put forward in the central macro-policy, at the specific level of urban implementation, still give way to urban construction, land transfer and investment. In fact, it is very clear that most of the current local debt is due to urban real estate over-development and urban construction overspread caused. However, it has not been the focus of the study to find out the causes of urban debt from a deep-seated perspective, or to explore the various institutional problems that need to be solved.

Economists are not keen to study cities, because the study of macro financial, monetary, fiscal and corporate policies is much more ambitious, and these reflect the state's right to participate in the discussion of politics, more in line with the imported theoretical system. For city managers, since they can not discuss the so-called more macro-economic and social problems at the city level, from their own point of view and standpoint, they should study the realistic interest problems that urgently need to be solved in urban development, might be a more practical option.

The best way to ensure the interests of the city is urban planning. Because all urban construction and spatial resources, including real estate construction, must be planned. Because of this, urban problems are regarded as technical problems, and become the problems of planning and design drawings, as well as some local problems that need to be solved urgently, such as traffic, community governance, public order and so on. It is because of the combination of various realistic factors that the cognition or research on cities in the current system is more technology-oriented, and deviates from the main axis of the overall development of the economy and society and the people-centered.

Because of the serious lag of cognition and research, some city managers have paid more attention to the material construction than to the soft environment, resulting in the lack of public service resources. It is precisely in today's rapidly urbanizing China that the direct demand related to population and urban residents is the direct inducement that affects various problems in economic and social development. And that little incentive, even if it spreads for infectious disease or so, can turn into a huge social crisis that affects the whole country and the world. In the future, to improve the level of urban governance, or to improve the "city" and "people" of the understanding, is how to solve the problem of serious shortage of public service resources, is to establish a people-centered social governance system.

A new understanding of urban governance

History often does not repeat itself in the same trajectory, and the economic and social risks that can arise from people are not limited to this epidemic alone, but may also be hidden in many other ways.

Our reminder of this epidemic is that, from the point of view of the immediate cause, attention should be paid to the prevention and control of infectious diseases and the establishment of a more effective epidemic prevention system; from the point of view of public opinion, society should be allowed to have transparent channels for the transmission of information, to prevent the human factors and administrative system factors hinder the response to sudden public events.

But from a deeper perspective, do we really understand the urban problem? Have we reflected more deeply on the economic and social problems that may arise in the development of megacities and megacities with so many tens of millions of people and a population of one million? Do we need to adapt our traditional structures of state-to-local governance, which have lasted for thousands of years, to the process of urbanization? Do we need to start thinking seriously about the essential differences between traditional local governance and modern urban governance?

The most important reason for the rapid spread of the epidemic from one city to the whole country is the massive population movement, which is beyond the scope of medicine, but it is only one aspect of the urban problem. The epidemic may also affect the employment of hundreds of millions of people in the future. It may involve the improvement and improvement of their quality of life and the survival of tens of millions of small and medium-sized enterprises, it involves how to distinguish the true information from the rumor in the public information dissemination and so on. Overall, the outbreak is a severe test of our fragile urbanization process.

In the context of China's urbanization process, it is necessary to reflect on the epidemic situation from more aspects and from a more comprehensive perspective, and to re-understand the various institutional problems in urban governance, to study the unique trajectory and Law of urban development in China. At the same time, summing up international experience, studying how to take urban issues as the top priority of national economic and social governance, and exploring urbanization paths that are more in line with national conditions and meet the development needs of modern society, i think this should be a challenge and an opportunity.

The writer is chief economist at the Center for Urban and small town reform and development in China
